<h1>HTML LISTS</h1>
<ol>
<h2>Definition</h2>
<p>An<strong> HTML List</strong> allows you to organize data on web pages into an<strong> ordered or unordered format</strong> to make the information easier to read and visually appealing. HTML Lists are very helpful for creating structured, accessible content in web development.</p>
<h2> 1.<u> <strong>ORDERED LIST</strong></u> </h2>
<p>An<strong> Ordered List </strong>display items in a sequence using numbers or letters .</p>
<p>Each items is defined using the ol tag.</p>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Numbers</li>
<li>Uppercase</li>
<li>Lowercase</li>
<li>Roman Numbers -Uppercase</li>
<li>Roman numbers -Lowercase</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Examples</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Apple</li>
<li>Mango</li>
<li>Orange</li>
<h2> 2.<u><strong>UNORDERED LIST</strong></u></h2>
<p>An<strong> unordered list </strong> displays items with bullet points instead of numbers.</p>
<p>It used when order of items does not matter.</p>
<p><strong>Types:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Circle</li>
<li>Disc</li>
<li>Square</li>
<li>None</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Examples</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Ready</li>
<li>Set</li>
<li>Go</li>
<h2> 3.<u><strong>NESTED LISTS</strong></u></h2>
<p>A <strong> Nested lists </strong> is a list placed in another list.</p>
<p>This  is useful for showing sub-items or hierichical data.</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<dl>
<dt>coffee</dt>
<dd>-hot drink</dd>
<dt>Juice</dt>
<dd>-cold drink</dd>
</dl>
</body>
